# Architecture

> Structural decisions for the Agents Relay Orchestration module.


## Architecture

---

---

## A1 Relay Orchestrator Architecture
**Status:** draft
**Depends on:** G2
**Tags:** stack:backend, module:relay

An LLM-based orchestrator would consume tokens for routing decisions, violating G3's token-efficiency mandate. It would also introduce non-determinism into flow execution. A deterministic state machine in Rust provides zero-token coordination, predictable routing, and compile-time safety.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Orchestrator (Rust)"
        O[PipelineEngine]
        F[FlowSpec Parser]
        H[Handoff Manager]
        C[Checkpoint Manager]
        B[Budget Tracker]
    end
    subgraph "Agent Turn"
        A[AgentInstance]
        T[ToolRegistry Filter]
        D[Multi-Provider Dispatch]
    end
    subgraph "AI Providers"
        AP[Anthropic]
        OP[OpenAI]
        LP[Local/Ollama]
    end
    subgraph "Specs (Ledger)"
        L[Jades / Ledger]
    end
    subgraph "Persistence"
        P[Checkpoint Store]
        R[Run Store]
        CS[Config Store]
    end

    O -->|parse| F
    O -->|generate| H
    O -->|save/load| C
    O -->|track| B
    O -->|spawn from config| A
    A -->|filtered| T
    A -->|chat via| D
    D -->|route| AP
    D -->|route| OP
    D -->|route| LP
    A -->|read/write| L
    C -->|serialize| P
    O -->|persist| R
    O -->|load configs| CS
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Deterministic Rust orchestrator | Zero token cost, predictable, fast, type-safe | Cannot adapt to novel flow patterns without code change |
| LLM-based orchestrator | Flexible, natural language flow definitions | Token cost per routing decision, non-deterministic, harder to test |
| Hybrid (LLM plans, Rust executes) | Flexibility + determinism | More complex, LLM still needed for plan generation |

- Positive: Flow execution is deterministic and unit-testable.
- Positive: No token spend on coordination.
- Negative: New flow patterns (e.g., conditional routing based on spec content) require code changes to `PipelineEngine`.
- Mitigation: FlowSpec supports `branch`, `loop`, and `on_fail` primitives that cover 95% of use cases.


