## A2 Agent Instance Lifecycle
**Status:** draft
**Depends on:** G1, G2
**Tags:** stack:backend, module:agent-config

Long-lived agent processes would accumulate context and state, defeating the token-efficiency goal. By spawning fresh instances per step, each agent starts with a clean, minimal context window. This also simplifies crash recovery — no need to restore agent memory, only the checkpoint.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Spawning: Orchestrator starts step
    Spawning --> ConfigResolving: Look up AgentConfig by profession
    ConfigResolving --> Running: Soul + Specs + Handoff + resolved Model loaded
    Running --> ToolCall: Agent invokes tool
    ToolCall --> Running: Tool result appended
    Running --> HandoffComplete: Agent calls handoff tool
    Running --> BudgetExceeded: Token limit reached
    Running --> Error: Panic / API failure
    Error --> Fallback: Try fallback model from ApiSource
    Fallback --> Running: Retry with fallback model
    Fallback --> Failed: All fallbacks exhausted
    HandoffComplete --> [*]: Instance dropped, checkpoint saved
    BudgetExceeded --> [*]: Forced handoff, budget note added
    Failed --> [*]: Run marked Failed, human notified
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Ephemeral per-step instances | Minimal context, easy recovery, cheap | Agent cannot learn across turns within a step |
| Long-lived instances with context window | Agent remembers earlier turns | Context grows, recovery harder, more tokens |
| Persistent agent processes with memory | Cross-run learning possible | Complex state management, not needed for relay |

- Positive: Maximum token efficiency.
- Positive: Crash recovery is trivial — just re-spawn from checkpoint.
- Negative: If an agent needs 5 turns to complete, each turn re-loads the same Soul + Specs. However, this is cheaper than maintaining a growing context.


