## A5 Frontend Composable State Architecture
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G8
**Tags:** stack:frontend, module:ui-system

An LLM-based orchestrator would consume tokens for routing decisions, violating G3's token-efficiency mandate. It would also introduce non-determinism into flow execution. A deterministic state machine in Rust provides zero-token coordination, predictable routing, and compile-time safety.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Frontend Composables"
        F[useForge.ts]
        R[useRelay.ts]
        S[useSpecs.ts]
        G[useGateInbox.ts]
        I[useItemRelations.ts]
        AS[useApiSources.ts]
        AC[useAgentConfigs.ts]
        P[useProject.ts]
    end
    subgraph "Vue Components"
        C[ChatView]
        V[SpecsView]
        L[RelayView]
        AV[ApiSourcesView]
        AE[AgentsConfigView]
    end

    F -->|session gates| G
    R -->|run gates| G
    G -->|renders| C
    R -->|invalidates| S
    S -->|finds item| I
    I -->|enriches| V
    R -->|uses agent configs| AC
    AC -->|reads api sources| AS
    F -->|uses api sources| AS
    AS -->|renders| AV
    AC -->|renders| AE
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Vue 3 Composables (singleton refs) | Zero boilerplate, matches existing code, tree-shakable, direct cross-import | No time-travel debugging; state is implicit |
| Pinia global store | DevTools support, mutations traceable | More boilerplate, refactor cost for existing composables |
| Redux/Vuex | Time-travel, predictable state updates | Massive overhead for a Vue 3 project |

- Positive: `useGateInbox` can import `useRelay` and `useForge` directly to listen for gate events without event bus indirection.
- Negative: Composable cross-imports create a soft dependency graph that is not explicitly declared.
- Mitigation: Document cross-cutting concerns in the Architecture ADR; avoid circular imports by keeping `useGateInbox` as the central hub.


